  "answer": "**The moth-and-candle (parwana/shama) is a classic Persianate poetic figure symbolizing the lover's self-annihilating devotion to the beloved, recurrent in Sufi-inspired Urdu ghazals and nazms. It appears nowhere in the Western or Indic philosophical texts of the corpus (e.g., no relevant \"moth\" or \"candle\" pairings in Cynewulf's *Andreas* or *Angirasa Smrti*, where \"candle\" means \"sun\" and \"moth\" is absent or literal). All instances are in the Urdu poetry subcorpus (transliterations/English translations).**\n\n### Works Using the Figure\nThese five works employ it explicitly (via parwana/shama or direct English equivalents in translation):\n\n1. **Bang-E-Dara Part 1** (*Allama Iqbal*, 1924): Frequent, e.g., the child gazes \"upon the candle's fire\" like \"a moth's desire\"[^1]; dedicated poems \"Shama\" (Candle), \"Shama-o-Parwana\" (Candle and Moth).[^2]\n\n2. **Bang-E-Dara Part 2** (*Allama Iqbal*, 1924): The soul addressed as \"a lone candle on a grave\" amid love's fire.[^3]\n\n3. **Bang-E-Dara Part 3** (*Allama Iqbal*, 1924): The poet tells \"the candle of my desolate dwelling: 'Your tresses are combed by the wing of a moth'\"; poem \"Shama aur Shair\" (Candle and Poet).[^4]\n\n4. **Diwan-E-Ghalib** (*Mirza Ghalib*): Pervasive metaphor, e.g., the candle gains \"endless burning\" from the beloved's face, grieving \"the moth’s desire\".[^5]\n\n5. **Diwan-E-Zauq** (*Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq*): \"Wings of the moth\" scattered around \"the tree of the candle\" as love's fruit.[^6]\n\n**No other works in the 37-text corpus use this figure (searches for \"moth candle\", \"moth flame\", English \"moth\"/\"candle\", or variants returned zero beyond these).**\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 15 \"Bacha aur Shama\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/15-bacha-aur-shama/translation/#p-4b705b).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 41 \"Shama-o-Parwana\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/41-shama-o-parwana/translation/#p-0d1630).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 2 \"Ilahi aql-e-khajista-pai ko zara si deewangi sikha de\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/02-ilahi-aql-e-khajista-pai-ko-zara-si-deewangi-sikha/translation/#p-e2ed35).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 19 \"Shama aur Shair\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/19-shama-aur-shair/translation/#p-8f74a7).\n\n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 173 \"Rukh-e-nigaar se hai soz-e-jaavedaani-e-shama\" [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/173-rukh-e-nigaar-se-hai-soz-e-jaavedaani-e-shama/translation/#p-8b3c23).\n\n[^6]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 18 \"Haath seena pe mere rakh ke kidhar dekhte ho\" [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/18-haath-seena-pe-mere-rakh-ke-kidhar-dekhte-ho/transliteration/#p-6bca5d).",
